Sangamiththa Stupa
 Image source : 
About one hundred thirty meters to the east of 
 lies a small stupa identified as the Sangamiththa Stupa.
Theri Sangamiththa ( also spelled Sangamitta, Sangamittha) was the daughter of the Indian emperor Asoka who arrived in Sri Lanka in the 249 BC with the southern branch of the original Sri Maha Bodhi in India.
The son of the emperor Asoka, the great Mahinda Thero and Theri Sangamitta lived in Sri Lanka helping the king to establish Buddhist philosophy in the country until they passed away.
It is said in ancient chronicles that the king Uttiya enshrined the ashes of Arhath Sangamitta Theri to the east of the Thuparama stupa. Archaeologists believe that this is the stupa mentioned in the chronicles.
